<isis lang="en">
    <stitle>TSI 01-03-03 - Incorrect Mounting of Shock Mounting Brackets will Result In Failure of Rear Upper Shock
        Absorber Mounting Bolts In 4x2 4700 LP Models Built Before January 1, 2000 with International Air Suspension
        Codes 14TAD, 14TAG, 14TAJ, 14TAK, and 14TBE
    </stitle>
    <tsi id="tsi010303" tsitype="truck">
        <tsinumber>01-03-03</tsinumber>
        <tsidate>September, 2001</tsidate>
        <subjectfile>SPRINGS</subjectfile>
        <subjectgroup>
            <subject>Incorrect Mounting of Shock Mounting Brackets will Result In Failure of Rear Upper Shock Absorber
                Mounting Bolts In 4x2 4700 LP Models Built Before January 1, 2000 with International Air Suspension
                Codes 14TAD, 14TAG, 14TAJ, 14TAK, and 14TBE
            </subject>
        </subjectgroup>
        <apply>
            <configure>
                <truckmodelgroup/>

                <truckmodel>4700
                    <daterange>
                        <enddate>01/01/2000</enddate>
                    </daterange>
                </truckmodel>
                <ucodegroup/>

                <ucode>14TAD</ucode>
                <ucode>14TAG</ucode>
                <ucode>14TAJ</ucode>
                <ucode>14TAK</ucode>
                <ucode>14TBE</ucode>
            </configure>
        </apply>
        <description>
            <geninfo>
                <para>The incorrect orientation of shock absorber mounting brackets allows excessive extension of the
                    shock absorber leading to premature failure of the mounting bolt.
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0103031">Figure 1</hotlnk>
                    and
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f0103032">Figure 2</hotlnk>
                    show correct orientation of the lower shock mounting brackets and the new service part upper
                    bracket.
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <caution>
                        <para>Incorrect installation of shock absorber brackets will result in premature failure.</para>
                    </caution>
                </specpara>
                <figure id="f0103031" figsize="pg-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G0103031.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="502px"
                             scalefitheight="208px" resolution="325"/>
                    <caption>Figure 1. Shock Absorber with Upper and Lower Mounting Brackets (Left Side Shown)</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. LEFT SHOCK MOUNTING BRACKET (LOWER)</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. LEFT SHOCK MOUNTING BRACKET (UPPER)</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
                <figure id="f0103032" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../tsifigures/G0103032.webp" type="webp" scalefit="1" scalefitwidth="248px"
                             scalefitheight="272px" resolution="100"/>
                    <caption>Figure 2. Lower Shock Absorber Mounting Bracket (Left Side Shown)</caption>
                </figure>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>The lower shock mounting bracket must be installed with the roll formed end oriented up
                            and inboard to the chassis as shown in
                            <hotlnk xrefid="f0103032">Figure 2</hotlnk>
                            .
                        </para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </geninfo>
        </description>
